               <head/>
               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85068469">
                  <summary>1 copy of Qaṣīdat al-Burdah by Sharaf al-Dīn Muhammad ibn Saʿīd al-Shanhājī al-Būṣīrī</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="Uk_RSPA_116-item1">
                     <locus from="1v" to="22r"/>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21179">Qaṣīdat al-Burdah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_21179">قصيدة البردة</title>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164658840.0x000001 viaf_90042754">Sharaf al-Dīn Muhammad ibn Saʿīd al-Shanhājī al-Būṣīrī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar" key="viaf_90042754">شرف الدين محمد بن سعيد بن حماد الصنهاجي البوصيري</persName>
                     </author>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar">بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم. امن تذكر جيران بذي سلم.</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar">وصلى الله على خير خلقه نبينا محمد وآله أجمعين برحمتك يا أرحم الراحمين.</explicit>
                     <note>
                        <p>Jones has written on f1r in Arabic script "min baḥr al-basīṭ", which was taken by Wilkins as the title of the work and it is under this name it appears in his catalogue. This actually means "in the basīṭ metre", which is the metre of the poem.</p>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Light woven paper.</support>
                        <extent>ff. ii+22+v
                <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>295</height>
                              <width>185</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>200</height>
                              <width>105</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>European numerals in pencil.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>The manuscript is in very good condition. There is some (presumably worm) damage but this has largely been repaired such that what were clearly once quite large holes are no longer present.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="8">
                           <p>Very neat layout of eight lines in one column per page.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     <summary>Excellent large calligraphic black naskh script.</summary>
                     <handNote script="Arabic" scope="major"/>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="initial">Gold and blue floral heading on f1v. Opening (ff1v-2r) decorated with gilded leaf design in margins. At the end of the poem, there is a golden illuminated endpiece.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="border">Ruled gilt margins. Verse markers are also gilded. The verses are outlined by a thin cloud-shaped gilded line.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Jones infrequently highlights sections of the poem with a curly bracket (e.g. f8r), writes out the metre of the poem (e.g. f8v) or translates individual words (e.g. f2v). There is at least one other hand that has written a marginal note on f3r.</p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Standard India Office half leather binding with marbled wine-colour end papers.</p>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>
                     <p/>
                  </accMat>
               </physDesc>
